THE RISK:
{
 "id": "ce-hyperscale-global-split-mirage",
 "title": "The DE×hyperscale anchor cell is a mirage: CE-7's hyperscale-owned share is far below the rescaled global 44%",
 "narrative": "seg.hyperscale rescales Synergy's global 48% flat onto Central Europe. But ~60% of Europe's operational hyperscaler self-build capacity sits in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden and Belgium — three of the four outside CE-7. Inside CE, hyperscale presence is mostly leased capacity inside Frankfurt and Amsterdam colo campuses, which Statista's 'colocation and scale colocation' figure already counts on the geography axis as colo MW. The cube therefore double-books the same megawatts — hyperscale on the segment axis, colo on the geo axis — and the implied beachhead cell (DE 0.50 × hyperscale 0.44 ≈ 22% of TAM as 'German hyperscale') largely does not exist as hyperscale-owned facilities. The real buyer of that capacity's PDUs is the colo operator or its integrator, with colo-grade requirements: tenant billing metering, multi-tenant DCIM. A product roadmap and sales motion built for hyperscale custom SKUs in Germany aims at a cell the market never populated.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "seg.hyperscale",
  "seg.colocation"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Synergy's 48% hyperscale share is global; CBRE-sourced reporting places ~60% of Europe's operational hyperscaler self-build in Ireland, Netherlands, Sweden and Belgium — a geography that barely overlaps CE-7 — while the model applies the global split flat with a 0.91 carve-out",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c0",
    "digest:seg-mix#c14",
    "ledger:seg.hyperscale"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Within CE-7, hyperscale demand is predominantly leased: European colocation remains significantly larger than self-build, FLAPD colo hubs (Frankfurt, Amsterdam in CE) absorb the hyperscale take-up, and the Statista geo denominator counts that same 'scale colocation' MW as colo — so the segment axis and geo axis book the same capacity to different segments",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c13",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c7",
    "digest:geo-region-denominator#c9"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "seg.hyperscale 0.44 overstates CE hyperscale-owned demand and understates the colo-operator cell; the venture's implied DE×hyperscale×large-operator beachhead is materially smaller, and the real buyers need colo-grade product (billing metering, multi-tenant DCIM), not hyperscale custom builds",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.hyperscale",
    "ledger:seg.colocation",
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "seg.hyperscale is the best-dressed node on the segment axis — 'triangulated' across multiple Synergy vintages with a tight 0.40–0.48 band. The flaw is not the number but its geography: a global capacity split cannot survive contact with a region whose hyperscale capacity is leased rather than owned, and no band on a correctly-triangulated global figure covers a regional composition error.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "A Europe- or CE-scoped capacity split (Synergy, CBRE or JLL) showing hyperscale-owned/self-build capacity ≥40% of CE-7 total — i.e., the global split does transfer.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.5,
  "rationale": "The 60%-outside-CE self-build concentration is directly sourced, and Frankfurt's status as a colo (not self-build) hub is well documented; residual uncertainty is how much leased hyperscale capacity should still be attributed to the hyperscale buyer for PDU-spec purposes. [evidence revision: The core geographic concentration premise is now directly corroborated by the CBRE-sourced DCD article (verbatim match to the hypothesis), strengthening confidence that CE-7 hyperscale self-build is well below the rescaled global share. Synergy confirms ~half of hyperscale capacity is leased, and Structure Research shows Frankfurt's hyperscale footprint is largely 'hyperscale colocation.' Residual uncertainty remains around how much leased hyperscale capacity should still be attributed to the hyperscale buyer for PDU-spec purposes (Synergy's wholesale-colocation tracker explicitly splits out a 'Hyperscale' segment within wholesale colo, suggesting the buyer/spec question is genuinely ambiguous rather than clearly favoring the colo operator). Modest upward revision from 0.4 to 0.5.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "seg.hyperscale",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.3,
   "note": "Hyperscale-owned CE share corrected for the self-build concentration outside CE-7"
  },
  {
   "nodeId": "seg.colocation",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.3,
   "note": "Mix-shift: leased 'scale colocation' capacity re-attributed to the colo-operator segment where the PDU purchasing decision actually sits"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Hyperscale self-build MW announced/operational by country",
   "where": "CBRE quarterly 'Europe Data Centres Figures'; hyperscaler capex-call site announcements for DE/PL/AT",
   "threshold": "CE-7 self-build share of Europe rising above ~25% would weaken the risk; staying ≤20% confirms it",
   "updates": "decreases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Publication of a Europe-scoped hyperscale/colo/enterprise capacity split",
   "where": "Synergy Research Europe releases; EUDCA State of European Data Centres",
   "threshold": "Europe hyperscale-owned share reported <35%",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Buy or derive a Europe-scoped segment split (Synergy Europe cut or CBRE self-build vs colo series) before locking the product roadmap to hyperscale requirements",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "seg.hyperscale",
   "note": "Directly de-risks the largest segment node with a regionally-scoped source"
  },
  {
   "action": "Spec the launch product for colo-operator requirements — billing-grade tenant metering, multi-tenant DCIM integration, retrofit form factors — since the CE cell that actually exists is colo-operated capacity serving hyperscale tenants",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Aligns the product with the real buyer of the double-booked megawatts"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "CBRE: European hyperscaler self-build capacity growth to outpace colocation supply growth",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "DatacenterDynamics (citing CBRE)",
   "date": "2026-02-20",
   "excerpt": "This new supply will be delivered across nine European countries, with 60 percent of Europe’s operational hyperscale self-build capacity located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium.",
   "url": "https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/cbre-european-hyperscaler-self-build-capacity-growth-to-outpace-colocation-supply-growth-but-supply-outpaces-take-up-in-weaker-than-expected-2025/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "On-Premise Data Center Capacity Being Increasingly Dwarfed by Hyperscalers and Colocation Companies",
   "sourceType": "analyst-estimate",
   "publisher": "Synergy Research Group",
   "date": "2023-07-12",
   "excerpt": "Approximately half of that hyperscale capacity is in own-built, owned data centers and half is in leased facilities.",
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/on-premise-data-center-capacity-being-increasingly-dwarfed-by-hyperscalers-and-colocation-companies",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Frankfurt DCI Report 2024: Data Centre Colocation, Hyperscale Cloud & Interconnection",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Structure Research",
   "date": "2024-06-24",
   "excerpt": "Hyperscale colocation is growing at a five-year CAGR of 26.1% and retail colocation is moving along at a 10.3% clip.",
   "url": "https://www.structureresearch.net/product/frankfurt-dci-report-2024-data-centre-colocation-hyperscale-cloud-interconnection/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/cbre-european-hyperscaler-self-build-capacity-growth-to-outpace-colocation-supply-growth-but-supply-outpaces-take-up-in-weaker-than-expected-2025/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "This new supply will be delivered across nine European countries, with 60 percent of Europe’s operational hyperscale self-build capacity located in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Belgium."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/on-premise-data-center-capacity-being-increasingly-dwarfed-by-hyperscalers-and-colocation-companies",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Approximately half of that hyperscale capacity is in own-built, owned data centers and half is in leased facilities."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.srgresearch.com/articles/the-flap-markets-bring-in-55-of-w-european-colocation-revenues-equinix-and-digital-realty-are-the-leaders",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "the metros of Frankfurt, London, Amsterdam and Paris (the so-called FLAP markets) together account for 55% of the Western European colocation market, based on retail and wholesale colocation revenues in Q2 2022"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.structureresearch.net/product/frankfurt-dci-report-2024-data-centre-colocation-hyperscale-cloud-interconnection/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Hyperscale colocation is growing at a five-year CAGR of 26.1% and retail colocation is moving along at a 10.3% clip."
  }
 ]
}

